----------------------------------------------------------------------
-- Whole-model verification summary
----------------------------------------------------------------------

-- Summary 1: Model defines core operation REQ_ATC_01 with initiator, target resources, channel, grant, pre/post states.
-- Summary 2: Structural invariants ensure authorization, access control, state change, and authentication.
-- Summary 3: Post-state reachability predicates verify rejection (Post1) and notification (Post2) scenarios.
-- Summary 4: Acceptance criteria and edge case assertions check overlapping assignment prevention.
-- Summary 5: Non-functional invariants included: channel limit, scalability (all actors initiate), usability (auth limit).
-- Assumption 1: Overlap is defined as two flight assignments using the same resource (slot/runway) at the same time, modeled via resource equality and finalized=false.
-- Assumption 2: Notification of conflict is performed via the Flight Assignment API, not the database.
-- Assumption 3: Reception of assignment changes is modeled as operations on resources FlightAssignmentAPIResource and FlightAssignmentDBResource.
-- Assumption 4: The system state change (rejection or notification) is reflected by a distinct post-state (Post1 or Post2).
-- Assumption 5: Safety Compliance Department initiates rejection and notification; Air Traffic Controllers initiate creation/modification.
-- Assumption 6: Edge cases assume sector distinction allows overlapping non-finalized assignments in different sectors.
-- Assumption 7: Non-functional requirements (performance, availability, scalability, usability) are approximated by structural constraints on channel count and target count.
-- Open issue 1: The model does not explicitly represent time or simultaneous usage; overlapping is implicit via resource sharing and finalized flags.
-- Open issue 2: The connection between REQ_ATC_01 operations and FlightAssignment sig is not enforced by invariants; only test predicates assume relationships.
-- Open issue 3: Sector and FlightAssignment sigs are defined but not integrated into the core operation facts; they appear only in edge case assertions.
-- Open issue 4: The availability non-functional fact was removed to avoid conflicts; its intended constraint is not represented.
-- Open issue 5: The spec includes a permission lattice and actor hierarchy that are not directly tied to the overlapping requirement.


